comments.body:
Unfortunately `has_nx` only includes stack nx checks in 0.16.6 (and main):

https://github.com/lief-project/LIEF/tree/0.16.6/include/LIEF/MachO/Binary.hpp#L579-L593

```cpp

  /// Check if the binary uses `NX` protection
  bool has_nx() const override {
    return !has_nx_stack();
  }

  /// Return True if the **heap** is flagged as non-executable. False otherwise
  bool has_nx_stack() const {
    return !header().has(Header::FLAGS::ALLOW_STACK_EXECUTION);
  }

  /// Return True if the **stack** is flagged as non-executable. False otherwise
  bool has_nx_heap() const {
    return !header().has(Header::FLAGS::NO_HEAP_EXECUTION);
  }
  ```

It seems like the ELF checks are also stack only (https://github.com/lief-project/LIEF/blob/c678f6bdfb3f3199b36e1f8df25f7432a2725f53/src/ELF/Binary.cpp#L1056-L1068)

```cpp
bool Binary::has_nx() const {
  if (const Segment* gnu_stack = get(Segment::TYPE::GNU_STACK)) {
    return !gnu_stack->has(Segment::FLAGS::X);
  }
  
  return false;
}
```

It seems that on most ELF systems the heap is implicitly not executable, I do find some mentions of a header value `PT_GNU_HEAP`, but I'm a bit confused as to whether or not this ELF header bit is actually [respected](https://gcc.gnu.org/legacy-ml/gcc-help/2012-02/msg00122.html), or implemented anywhere, or if heap executability is determined by the kernel, grepping for it in the kernel yields no result.
